<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05018g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05018g">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05018g"> 18(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> neesings</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Job is supposed to refer to one of these &ldquo;great whales&rdquo; in his fantastic description of leviathan, who in the Revised Version is degraded into a crocodile. According to the great Rabbi Kimchi it is the same animal which is mentioned in the Creation Story, and the largest fish in the sea. But whether leviathan was a whale or a crocodile, no extant specimens of either in the least resemble Job&apos;s description. Where are the &ldquo;comely proportions,&rdquo; the pyrotechnic <mark>&ldquo;neesings,&rdquo;</mark> the eyes &ldquo;like the eyelids of the morning,&rdquo; and the hot breath that could light a fire without matches? <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) 148</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <i>Neese</i> (Elizabethan English) = sneeze, or snort.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c02020e" href="c02all.htm#c02020e">VI.C.02:020(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
